SIMPLE: secrete
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Secrete
<hw>Se*crete"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Secreted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Secreting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>secretus</ets>
separated, secret, hidden, p. p. of <ets>secernere</ets>. See
<er>Secret</er>, and cf. <er>Discrete</er>, <er>Discreet</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To deposit in a place of hiding; to hide; to conceal;
<as>as, to <ex>secrete</ex> stolen goods; to <ex>secrete</ex> one's
self</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>To separate from the blood and
elaborate by the process of secretion; to elaborate and emit as a
secretion. See <er>Secretion</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why one set of cells should <qex>secrete</qex> bile, another urea,
and so on, we do not know.</q> <rj><qau>Carpenter.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To conceal; hide. See <er>Conceal</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Secretion</ent>⟦br⟧
